:::summary
John Locke (1632–1704) was the English philosopher whose ideas about natural rights, consent of the governed, and limited government became the philosophical foundation of the American founding. His *Two Treatises of Government* (1689) argued that legitimate government derives from the consent of the governed and exists solely to protect God-given rights to life, liberty, and property — ideas that Thomas Jefferson wove directly into the Declaration of Independence and that continue to define the ideals of the free world.
:::

